  "prompt": "Why is the value of Indian rupee falling?",
  "response": "The value of the Indian rupee has been falling due to several interconnected factors:\n\n1. Economic Factors:\n- Higher inflation rates\n- Widening trade deficit\n- Slowing economic growth\n- Increased import costs, especially crude oil\n- Foreign investors withdrawing funds\n\n2. Global Economic Conditions:\n- Strong US dollar\n- US Federal Reserve's interest rate hikes\n- Global economic uncertainty\n- Geopolitical tensions\n- COVID-19 pandemic impact\n\n3. External Pressures:\n- Increased crude oil prices\n- Reduced foreign investment\n- Capital outflows\n- Depreciation of other emerging market currencies\n\n4. Domestic Monetary Policies:\n- Reserve Bank of India's interventions\n- Monetary policy adjustments\n- Lower foreign exchange reserves\n\n5. International Trade:\n- Higher import expenditure\n- Lower export earnings\n- Reduced remittances\n- Global supply chain disruptions\n\n6. Investor Sentiment:\n- Reduced confidence in emerging markets\n- Concerns about economic stability\n- Perception of economic challenges\n\nThese factors collectively contribute to the depreciation of the Indian rupee against major currencies like the US dollar. The situation is dynamic and can change based on global and domestic economic conditions.",
